**The implementation uses a three-part pattern common in drag-and-drop UIs:**

1. **`handleBarClick` (lines 109‚Äì121)** ‚Äî The click handler on the gradient bar. It calculates the position percentage from the click's `clientX` coordinate via `positionFromEvent`, creates a new white stop (`#ffffff`) at that position, appends it to the stops array, auto-selects it, and emits the change.

2. **Marker exclusion (line 112)** ‚Äî `if ((e.target as HTMLElement).dataset.marker) return;` prevents the "add stop" logic from firing when clicking an existing stop marker. Each marker has `data-marker="true"` (line 228), so the bar click handler early-returns when the click target is a marker rather than empty space.

3. **`positionFromEvent` (lines 62‚Äì67)** ‚Äî Converts a `clientX` pixel coordinate into a 0‚Äì100 percentage relative to the bar's bounding rect, clamped to prevent out-of-range values.

`‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ`

**How it works end-to-end:**
- The gradient bar `<div>` at line 211 has `onClick={handleBarClick}` and `cursor: "crosshair"` to signal interactivity
- Click on empty space ‚Üí `handleBarClick` fires ‚Üí `positionFromEvent` converts pixels to percentage ‚Üí new stop inserted ‚Üí `emit()` calls `onChange` ‚Üí parent re-renders with updated stops
- The new stop is auto-selected (`setSelectedIndex(next.length - 1)`) so the color picker / position controls immediately appear for it

One minor observation: the interpolated color for new stops is hardcoded to `#ffffff` (line 115) with the comment "simple: just use white." A more polished approach would interpolate between the two nearest neighbor stops' colors, but for a v1 this is reasonable.

